  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "PT",
    "text": "LAURA (DAUGHTER): Also, I want to say when I was a child that I felt that I was different. Other kids really couldn't relate to the information that we got or stories in our home. And other children had grandparents, and many aunts and uncles. And from about the time that I was five, I was aware that my relatives were killed. I was named after a young woman who was killed. My brother and sister were named after relatives who were murdered. And as a result of that, I think that children of Holocaust survivors really do lose a great part of the innocence of their childhood. Even if my mother or my father didn't dwell on it, we still were aware of their pain and internalized a lot of that pain. SUSAN (DAUGHTER): Our names constantly were our roots. LAURA (DAUGHTER): Yeah. SUSAN (DAUGHTER): Mine was-- LAURA (DAUGHTER): When I see conflicts in the world today, I often think that when the war is over or the suffering is over that the next generation is still going to suffer because of all of the stories and being deprived of relatives.",
